<br>
NOTE:  ONLY DO 1 LENS AT A TIME!<br>
<br>
1] Get a piece of plexiglass, and cut it approimately 1/4&quot; larger than your old lens (1/4&quot; all the way around).<br>
<br>
2] Preheat your oven to somewhere between 250-300 degrees, and prepare a clean cookie sheet (the newer, the better).<br>
<br>
3] Have potholders and a cool washcloth nearby.<br>
<br>
4] Heat the lens for 1-2 minutes, keeping an eye on  it as it heats.  <br>
<br>
5] After 1-2 minutes, when the lens looks pliable (don't melt it!), remove it from the oven and insert it into the helmet.  (I recommend using the wet cloth to do this.)  You should be able to feel that the lens is pliable when you pick it up.<br>
<br>
6] When you insert it into the helmet, apply constant pressure to the edges.  If the lens is warm enough, it will easily form to the shape of the eye holes.  If it is not pliable, put it back in the oven for another 20-30 seconds.<br>
<br>
7] I molded the edges of the lens down to the helmet all the way around.  Once I had the lens where I wanted it, I left the cool cloth on it while it cooled.<br>
<br>
8]   When the 1st lens has cooled, remove it an repeat the steps for the 2nd lens.<br>
<br>
When I had completed both lenses, I taped them in place and double-checked the fit.  I wanted the lenses to fit a little tighter in a few places, so I used a heat gun to warm the lens again and fit it back into the eye hole.  (The heat gun worked very well.)<br>
<br>
Using the extra 1/4&quot; lip that I created, I put some JB Weld epoxy between the helmet and the lens.  Be careful not to put too much under the lens, or it will squirt out and get on te front of your lens.  As the epoxy dried, I added a second coating around the edges to seal it down.  You could also reinforce the edges with hot glue, tape, or whatever you prefer. <p>Rory<br>
